Beginner Level Hindustani vocal plan for absolute beginners, designed to fit an 8–12 week timeframe. It emphasizes breathing, basic swaras, simple rhythm, and one easy Bandish in a beginner raga (Yaman is a common starting point). 

1) Beginner Level Goals 
- Develop diaphragmatic breathing and relaxed posture
- Sing clear Sa Re Ga Ma Pa Dha Ni Sa with accurate pitch using a tanpura drone
- Pronounce sargam clearly; begin simple rising/falling patterns
- Understand Teentaal (16-beat) with basic clapping
- Learn 1 simple Bandish in a beginner-friendly raga (e.g., Yaman or Bhairav) with correct intonation
- Begin basic sur (meend, kan) at a rudimentary level
- Start recording weekly to monitor progress

2) Week-by-week Plan (Absolute Beginner)

Week 1–2: Breathing, Posture, Sa Re Ga Ma
- Daily practice 20–30 minutes
  - Diaphragmatic breathing (5 minutes)
  - Posture and jaw/neck relaxation (5 minutes)
  - Lip trills, humming, simple sirens (10 minutes)
  - Sing Sa Re Ga Ma with clear enunciation, using tanpura on Sa (5-7 minutes)
- Home task: record 1 minute singing Sa to Sa, review for even tone

Week 3–4: Sargam Practice and Basic Intonation
- Daily practice 30–40 minutes
  - Warm-up (5 minutes)
  - Sargam practice: Sa Re Ga Ma Pa Dha Ni Sa ascending and descending (10-15 minutes)
  - Simple scales with pitch accuracy (15-20 minutes)
  - Intro to light ornamentation: basic meend on Sa–Re and Sa–Ga (5-10 minutes)
- Rhythm: clap Teentaal for 1–2 cycles to feel the pulse
- Repertoire: learn 1 simple Bandish in Yaman or Bhairav (lyrics optional) with basic pronunciation

Week 5–6: Raga Introduction & Simple Phrases
- Daily practice 40–50 minutes
  - Review Sa Re Ga Ma with tanpura
  - Raga selection for beginners: Yaman (gentle) or Bhairav (more gravitas)
  - Learn basic aroha/avaroha phrases
  - Practice 2–3 simple pakad (signature phrases)
- Bandish practice: 1 simple Bandish in chosen raga, focus on intonation with drone
- Ear training: identify simple intervals by listening and reproducing

Week 7–8: Basic Rhythm & First Performance Prep
- Daily practice 45–60 minutes
  - Sargam plus basic taali (rhythm with claps)
  - Learn a second Bandish or expand the first with a new line
  - Prepare a short 2–3 minute practice performance:
    - 1 minute simple alap-like exploration
    - 1 minute Bandish section
    - 30 seconds basic taan-like phrases (slow)
- Recording: record your 2–3 minute practice and review for intonation and rhythm

3) Essential Practice Routine (repeatable)
- Morning (optional): 5–10 minutes breath work
- Mid-day: 15–20 minutes warm-ups and sargam
- Evening: 15–30 minutes focused on current Bandish and raga phrases
- Weekly: 1 recorded performance; seek feedback if possible

4) Core Concepts to Master Early
- Breath control: diaphragmatic breathing, even phrase length
- Clear pronunciation: crisp sargam syllables and lyrics
- Pitch accuracy: use tanpura drone; practice slowly
- Raga mood: sense the basic emotion of the chosen ragas
- Simple ornamentation: gentle meend and kan

5) Basic Assessment & Milestones (Beginner)
- Week 4: sing Sa Re Ga Ma with steady tone; basic sargam accuracy
- Week 6: complete 1 Bandish with true intonation; 1–2 simple phrases
- Week 8: 2 Bandish pieces prepared; 2–3 minute practice with basic rhythm

6) Tips to Stay on Track
- Maintain a simple practice log noting what worked and what didn’t
- Record weekly and compare improvements
- If a note feels off, check breath support, jaw relaxation, and throat posture
- Stay hydrated; avoid throat strain; rest voice if tired
- Seek feedback from a mentor or a singing friend

7) Optional Add-ons (as you progress)
- Affordable tanpura app for ongoing drone
- Keyboard or small harmonium to accompany practice
- Metronome app for steady tempo
- Listen to master renditions of your chosen raga
